  "prompt": "What are the legal definitions of money laundering?",
  "response": "The legal definitions of money laundering can vary slightly depending on the jurisdiction, but the core concept remains the same: **engaging in activities that conceal or disguise the true nature, source, location, disposition, movement, or ownership of illegally obtained property, making it appear legitimate.**\n\nHere's a breakdown of the key components and common definitions, drawing from international standards and specific examples:\n\n**Core Concepts Present in Most Definitions:**\n\n*   **Illicit Proceeds/Criminal Proceeds:** The property (assets, money, etc.) derived from criminal activity.  This is the \"dirty money.\"\n*   **Concealment/Disguise:**  Actions taken to hide the true source, ownership, location, or nature of the illicit proceeds. This is the key element of money laundering.\n*   **Legitimization/Integration:**  The process of making the dirty money appear clean and re-entering it into the legitimate financial system.\n\n**Key International Standards (often influencing national laws):**\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF):**  The FATF is an inter-governmental body that sets international standards to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.  Their definition is widely adopted and influences national laws.  While they don't have a single, simple definition, their standards require criminalizing the following:\n\n    *   **The conversion or transfer of property, knowing that such property is derived from a criminal offense, for the purpose of concealing or disguising the illicit origin of the property or of helping any person who is involved in the commission of the predicate offense to evade",
